Class NestedEntityPropertyController

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.foreach.across.modules.entity.registry.properties.NestedEntityPropertyController
  • All Implemented Interfaces:

    public class NestedEntityPropertyController
extends Object
implements EntityPropertyController, ConfigurableEntityPropertyController<EntityPropertyBindingContext,Object>
    EntityPropertyController implementation for a nested property, the property value of the parent EntityPropertyDescriptor actually supplies the binding context of the child controller.

    3.2.0

      • bulkValueFetcher

        public ConfigurableEntityPropertyController<EntityPropertyBindingContext,Object> bulkValueFetcher(Function<Collection<EntityPropertyBindingContext>,Map<EntityPropertyBindingContext,Object>> valueFetcher)
        Description copied from interface: ConfigurableEntityPropertyController
        Set the value fetching function that should be used for retrieving this property value in bulk from a collection of entities. Setting a non-null bulk fetcher should automatically also set ConfigurableEntityPropertyController.optimizedForBulkValueFetching(boolean) to true.

        Custom implementations should preferably return an IdentityHashMap to ensure that all input items have a corresponding value entry. Even if they are equals, separate entries are still expected. The order of the items returned is not important.

      • applyValue

        public boolean applyValue(EntityPropertyBindingContext context,
                          EntityPropertyValue propertyValue)
        Description copied from interface: EntityPropertyController
        Apply the current value of the property to the owning entity. Usually relevant for properties that modify the entity itself, but do not persist any data outside of the entity.

        Applying the property value has different semantics than EntityPropertyController.save(EntityPropertyBindingContext, EntityPropertyValue). The latter is meant for storing the actual property value whereas applying the value implies that the final store will happen transitively through the context (entity) to which the property value is applied.

        Applying a property value might happen several times during a binding process, so operations should be idempotent. Applying values usually happens right after regular data-binding but before validation, whereas EntityPropertyController.save(EntityPropertyBindingContext, EntityPropertyValue) is usually only called a single time after successful validation.

        A single controller implements usually either applyValue(EntityPropertyBindingContext, EntityPropertyValue) or EntityPropertyController.save(EntityPropertyBindingContext, EntityPropertyValue).

        Specified by:
        applyValue in interface EntityPropertyController
        Parameters:
        context - binding context
        propertyValue - value context holder
        Returns:
        true if value has been set
        See Also:
        EntityPropertyController.save(EntityPropertyBindingContext, EntityPropertyValue)

      • getOrder

        public int getOrder()
        Description copied from interface: EntityPropertyController
        The order in which this controller should be applied. Defaults to EntityPropertyController.AFTER_ENTITY meaning the controller methods will be executed after the equivalent entity methods. This is appropriate for custom properties that do not operate on the entity itself but require the entity to have been processed fully.
